STUDENT PERFORMANCE ANALYSIS

COLUMN DESCRIPTIONS:¶

Column Name Description
Student_idText or mixed-type identifier for each student
NameFull name of the student
GenderCategorical data: ['Other', 'Male', 'Female']
AgeAge of the student. Example values: 15, 17
Grade_levelNumeric representation of grade level (e.g., 9, 10, 12)
Math_scoreMath exam score (0–100 scale)
Reading_scoreReading exam score (0–100 scale)
Writing_scoreWriting exam score (0–100 scale)
Attendance_rateAttendance percentage. Example: 94.66%
Parent_educationCategorical: Parent's highest education level (e.g., "Master's", "Bachelor's", "PhD", "High School")
Study_hoursAverage daily hours spent studying
Internet_accessWhether the student has internet access at home: Yes or No
Lunch_typeType of lunch program: 'Free or reduced' or 'Standard'
Extra_activitiesParticipation in extracurricular activities: Yes or No
Final_resultFinal academic outcome: Pass or Fail

EXPLORATORY DATA ANALYSIS (EDA):¶

COUNT PLOT¶

In [30]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.countplot(x='gender', data=df, order=df['gender'].value_counts().index, palette='pastel')
plt.title('Count Plot of Gender')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
  • The dataset shows a higher number of entries for 'Male' compared to 'Female', indicating a gender imbalance. This should be considered when analyzing or modeling to avoid biased outcomes.

HISTOGRAM¶

In [33]:
df.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).hist(bins=30, figsize=(15, 12), color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')
plt.suptitle('Histograms of Numerical Features', fontsize=16)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
  • Most numerical features appear right-skewed, indicating that many values cluster at the lower end with a long tail toward higher values. Some features show potential outliers, which may need to be addressed before modeling.

DIST PLOT¶

In [36]:
sns.distplot(df['attendance_rate'],kde=True,bins=10)
plt.title("Dist Plot of Attendance Rate")
plt.show()
  • The distribution of attendance_rate is left-skewed, with most students having high attendance (above 80%). A small tail toward the lower end suggests a minority with significantly lower attendance, which might be worth investigating.

HEAT MAP¶

In [39]:
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))
sns.heatmap(df.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f")
plt.title('Correlation Heatmap of Numerical Features')
plt.show()
  • The heatmap shows a strong positive correlation between math_score, reading_score, and writing_score, suggesting academic performance is generally consistent across subjects. A mild positive correlation is seen between attendance_rate and scores, while age appears to have little to no correlation with academic performance.

BAR CHART¶

In [42]:
pd.crosstab(df['age'], df['extra_activities']).plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6), colormap='tab20')

plt.ylabel('Count')

plt.show()
  • The chart reveals that students aged 14 to 16 are the most actively involved in a wide range of extracurricular activities. Younger students, especially those under age 12, show much lower participation. This may suggest that schools or parents begin emphasizing extracurriculars more as students progress into middle or high school.

DBSCAN(Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise):¶

  • DBSCAN effectively identified noise and outlier customers and grouped customers in dense clusters
In [58]:
epsilon=0.5
min_samples=5
dbscan=DBSCAN(eps=epsilon,min_samples=min_samples)
labels=dbscan.fit_predict(x_reduced)
In [59]:
np.unique(labels)
Out[59]:
array([-1,  0], dtype=int64)
In [60]:
unique_labels = set(labels)
colors = [plt.cm.Spectral(each) for each in np.linspace(0, 1, len(unique_labels))]
for k, col in zip(unique_labels, colors):
    if k == -1:
        col = [0, 0, 0, 1]  

    class_member_mask = (labels == k)    #Creates a boolean array to identify points that belong to cluster k.
    xy = x_reduced[class_member_mask]    #Apply the mask to X_reduced to get all data points in cluster k.
    plt.plot(xy[:, 0], xy[:, 1], 'o', markerfacecolor=tuple(col), markeredgecolor='k', markersize=10)
plt.title("DBSCAN Clustering on Student Dataset (PCA-reduced to 2 dimensions)")
plt.xlabel("Principal Component 1")
plt.ylabel("Principal Component 2")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

KMEAN CLUSTERING¶

  • The K-Means algorithm effectively segmented the customers in the marketing dataset into distinct and meaningful groups based on purchasing behavior and demographic characteristics.
In [85]:
wcss = []
for i in range(1,13):
    kmeans=KMeans(n_clusters=i,init='k-means++',random_state=42)    
    kmeans.fit(x_reduced)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)
plt.plot(range(1,13),wcss)
plt.title('The elbow method')
plt.xlabel('no. of clusters')
plt.ylabel('wcss value')
plt.show()

AGGLOMERITIVE CLUSTERING:¶

  • Agglomerative Clustering, a type of hierarchical clustering, was successfully applied to segment the customers in the marketing dataset. This method builds clusters step-by-step by merging the most similar data points, which results in a tree-like structure called a dendrogram.
In [75]:
dendrogram=sch.dendrogram(sch.linkage(df,method='ward'))
plt.title('dendrogram')
plt.xlabel('data points')
plt.ylabel('euclidean distance')
plt.show()
In [76]:
ahc=AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=3,metric='euclidean',linkage='ward')
y_ahc=ahc.fit_predict(x_reduced)
